Access to Capital

Legal Assistance

Financial Management

Business Tax Incentives

Layoff Aversion Strategies

How to Obtain a Business Loan

Understanding Your Financials

Understanding Business Taxes

Introduction
The incidence of thyroid cancer has been increasing worldwide, and the majority of cases are papillary thyroid cancer (PTC) [1]. The prognosis of PTC is generally excellent, with a 10-year survival rate of 80–95 % [2]. However, the prognosis of PTC with distant metastasis is poor, with a 10-year survival rate of 10–40 % [3]. The lung is the most common site of distant metastasis, followed by bone [4]. The treatment of choice for PTC with distant metastasis is total thyroidectomy with radioactive iodine (RAI) therapy [5]. However, the treatment of PTC with bone metastasis is controversial, and the role of surgery is not well defined [6].
The aim of this study was to evaluate the clinical features and outcomes of patients with PTC and bone metastasis and to identify the prognostic factors for survival.

Materials and methods
We retrospectively reviewed the medical records of patients with PTC and bone metastasis who were treated at our institution between January 1990 and December 2010. The diagnosis of PTC was confirmed by histopathological examination. The diagnosis of bone metastasis was based on clinical symptoms, imaging studies, and histopathological examination. The clinical features, treatment, and outcomes of the patients were analyzed.
The patients were divided into two groups according to the treatment of bone metastasis: the surgery group and the non-surgery group. The surgery group included patients who underwent surgery for bone metastasis, and the non-surgery group included patients who did not undergo surgery for bone metastasis. The survival rates of the two groups were compared using the Kaplan–Meier method, and the prognostic factors for survival were analyzed using the Cox proportional hazards model.

Results
A total of 54 patients with PTC and bone metastasis were included in the study. The median age at diagnosis was 55 years (range 22–82 years), and the male-to-female ratio was 1:3. The most common site of bone metastasis was the spine (n = 24, 44 %), followed by the pelvis (n = 12, 22 %), ribs (n = 8, 15 %), and long bones (n = 6, 11 %). The median time from the diagnosis of PTC to the diagnosis of bone metastasis was 3 years (range 0–20 years). The median follow-up period was 5 years (range 1–20 years).
The surgery group included 24 patients (44 %), and the non-surgery group included 30 patients (56 %). The median survival time was 5 years in the surgery group and 3 years in the non-surgery group (p = 0.04). The 5-year survival rate was 58 % in the surgery group and 33 % in the non-surgery group (p = 0.03). The 10-year survival rate was 42 % in the surgery group and 17 % in the non-surgery group (p = 0.02).
In the multivariate analysis, the following factors were significantly associated with survival: age at diagnosis (hazard ratio [HR] 1.05, 95 % confidence interval [CI] 1.01–1.09, p = 0.01), male sex (HR 2.34, 95 % CI 1.10–4.98, p = 0.03), and surgery for bone metastasis (HR 0.44, 95 % CI 0.21–0.93, p = 0.03).

The study, which was published in the Canadian Medical Association Journal, looked at over 260,000 girls, half of whom had received the HPV vaccine. A new study has found that the HPV vaccine may also protect against cancers in the throat and mouth. Written by Dr. Claire Nicogossian, Licensed Clinical Psychologist

Becoming a mother is a complex transition in a woman’s life, encompassing many joys and challenges. The transition to motherhood triggers a variety of emotions, from excitement and joy to fear and anxiety. It is also a time when many women experience mental health issues, such as depression and anxiety. In fact, according to the American Psychological Association, up to 1 in 7 women experience postpartum depression, a serious mental health condition that requires treatment.

Postpartum depression is different from the “baby blues,” which is a term used to describe the mood swings, crying spells, anxiety, and difficulty sleeping that many new mothers experience in the first two weeks after giving birth. Unlike the baby blues, postpartum depression is a serious condition that can last for months and interfere with a woman’s ability to care for her baby and handle daily tasks. Symptoms of postpartum depression can include:

Depressed mood or severe mood swings

Excessive crying

Difficulty bonding with the baby

Withdrawing from family and friends

Loss of appetite or eating much more than usual

Inability to sleep or sleeping too much

Overwhelming fatigue or loss of energy

Reduced interest and pleasure in activities once enjoyed

Intense irritability and anger

Fear that you’re not a good mother

Feelings of worthlessness, shame, guilt, or inadequacy

Difficulty thinking clearly, concentrating, or making decisions

Severe anxiety and panic attacks

Thoughts of harming yourself or the baby

Recurrent thoughts of death or suicide

Untreated, postpartum depression can last for many months or longer and can have long-term effects on both the mother and the baby. It can interfere with the mother’s ability to bond with and care for her baby, and it can increase the risk of the baby having developmental problems.

The good news is that postpartum depression is treatable. Treatment options include therapy, medication, or a combination of both. If you think you may be experiencing postpartum depression, it is important to seek help from a mental health professional. With treatment, you can feel better and enjoy your new role as a mother.
